### II. Test-First Development (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

Every feature MUST have tests written before implementation code. The test
directory structure ({{TEST_STRUCTURE}}) MUST be maintained. All tests MUST
pass via `{{TEST_COMMAND}}` before any code is merged.

### III. Workspace Isolation and Security Boundaries

All file-system operations MUST resolve within the configured workspace root.
Path traversal attempts MUST be rejected.

### IV. CLI Workspace Containment (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

Agents MUST NOT create, modify, or delete any file or directory outside the
current working directory tree.

### V. Destructive Command Approval (NON-NEGOTIABLE)

All destructive terminal commands MUST require operator approval before
execution, regardless of permissive mode flags. Destructive commands include:
file/directory deletion, force-overwrite, system config changes, VCS history
alteration, data drops, system-level package changes, and untrusted code execution.

### VI. Safety Modes for Risky Work

When work has elevated blast radius, agents MUST enter an explicit safety mode before proceeding:

* **careful** — enumerate risks and require approval before destructive or high-impact actions
* **freeze-scope** — constrain edits to a declared directory or subsystem boundary
* **investigate-first** — gather evidence before proposing or applying fixes

### Capability Overlay — agent-intercom

When the `agent-intercom` capability pack is installed, agents MUST also follow
`.github/instructions/agent-intercom.instructions.md` and treat operator visibility as
part of the normal workflow:

* establish heartbeat / ping visibility at session start and during long-running work
* broadcast milestone progress for planning, implementation, review, verification, and closure
* route destructive terminal commands and destructive file operations through the configured intercom approval workflow
* use transmit / standby style operator waits when blocked on clarification, approval, or handoff
* warn clearly when intercom is unavailable and treat remote approval as unavailable rather than silently bypassed

### Capability Overlay — agent-engram

When the `agent-engram` capability pack is installed, agents MUST also follow
`.github/instructions/agent-engram.instructions.md` and treat indexed retrieval as part of the
normal workflow:

* prefer engram MCP tools for context-related search before grep, glob, or broad file reading
* verify the daemon / workspace binding state before relying on indexed search results
* use symbol lookup, call-graph, and impact-analysis operations for blast-radius questions before manual caller hunting
* refresh the index when results are stale after out-of-band edits
* fall back to file-based search only when indexed results are unavailable, insufficient, or the query is truly text-oriented

### Capability Overlay — backlogit

When the `backlogit` capability pack is installed, agents MUST also follow
`.github/instructions/backlogit.instructions.md` and treat the configured backlog tool as
the operational system of record for planning and execution state:

* prefer registry-backed backlogit MCP / CLI operations over ad hoc markdown scanning when querying task state
* use queue-aware and dependency-aware operations when selecting or sequencing work
* persist session continuity through backlogit memory / checkpoint operations when the registry advertises them
* record meaningful comments and commit associations for traceability when those operations are available
* refresh the backlog index after out-of-band edits before trusting query results

